About
Get ready for a breathtaking new attraction, combining an exhilarating active outdoor challenge with a completely unique perspective on the Capital.Prepare yourself for an unforgettable 90 minute experience which will take you on an uplifting expedition across the roof of the world's most popular entertainment venue. Enjoy spectacular 360 degree views of London from our viewing platform in the centre of the roof, before finishing with a thrilling descent back to base to complete your adventure.
Duration: 2-3 hours

The area

Address
Neighborhood: Greenwich
Greenwich Mean Time starts here, so to speak, as the very concept of global time was established at Royal Observatory, just one of several buildings of architectural interest in Greenwich. Indeed, the whole of Greenwich's historic town center, its Royal Park and a number of related buildings (and one world famous ship, the Cutty Sark) make up the UNESCO World Heritage site known as Maritime Greenwich. Today a laser beam is shot out across the night sky from the Observatory to mark the location of the Prime Meridian. Other bold (some say brash) 21st century additions to the area include landmarks such as The O2 entertainment complex (previously known as the Millennium Dome) and the Air Line cable cars, which offer scenic transport across the Thames between North Greenwich and the Royal Docks.
How to get there
  • North Greenwich • 2 min walk

  • Rama R
    London, United Kingdom711 contributions
    Fun experience.
    We had booked the 11:30 am slot on our daughter's birthday which fell on a Saturday. The weather showed clear skies when I booked a few weeks ahead, but that morning it was rainy, windy and cold. I really thought we had messed up our girl's big day, but thankfully just as we were all kitted up to start climbing, everything cleared up and the sun shone brightly down upon us. We could see all the landmarks from the observation deck on the top of the O2. The climb itself was easy though it is a little stressful in the ankles when you are doing the steepest ascent (30°). The descent is much simpler. The whole experience takes about 1.5 hours from registering to visiting the gift shop to collect your photos (includes a briefing session, getting kitted up and photos). This is a good activity for a day out in London.

Is there parking?
Written July 8, 2021
Glass half full
London, United Kingdom
171 contributions
Yes, we parked close to the O2 in one of their designated car parks called “Car Park 2”. They were doing Covid testing but there was still plenty of spaces. As you about to leave go to the round customer service desk in the entrance lobby inside the O2 and they can validate your ticket for some hours free parking as you went to Up@O2. Then we paid the balance at the machines in the carpark. It was reasonable. Suggest you also call Up@O2 to check this is still the case, as they were very friendly and helpful.
